cession": "MS:1002846", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/q2170422a.raw"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/L20192001337b na rep.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/L2171273a.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/L2171273b.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/L2171274a.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/L2172466a.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/L2172466b.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/L2172468a.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/q2170421a.msf"}, {"accession": "MS:1002849", "name": "Search engine output file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488/q2170422a.msf"}], "description": "Histone post-translational modifications (PTMs) are critical for processes such as transcription. The more notable among these are the non-acetyl histone lysine acylation modifications such as crotonylation, butyrylation and succinylation. However, the biological relevance of these PTMs is not fully understood because their regulation is largely unknown. Here, we set out to investigate whether the main histone acetyltransferases in budding yeast, Gcn5 and Esa1, possess crotonyltransferase activity. In vitro studies revealed that the Gcn5-Ada2-Ada3 (ADA) and Esa1-Yng2-Epl1 (Piccolo NuA4) histone acetyltransferase complexes have the capacity to crotonylate histones. Mass spectrometry analysis revealed that ADA and Piccolo NuA4 crotonylate lysines in the N-terminal tails of histone H3 and H4, respectively. Functionally, we show that crotonylation selectively affects gene transcription in vivo in a manner dependent on Gcn5 and Esa1. Thus, we identify the Gcn5- and Esa1-containing ADA and Piccolo NuA4 complexes as bona fide crotonyltransferases that promote crotonylation-dependent transcription.", "fullDatasetLinks": [{"accession": "MS:1002852", "name": "Dataset FTP location", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2019/11/PXD015488"}, {"accession": "MS:1001930", "name": "PRIDE project URI", "value": "http://www.ebi.ac.uk/pride/archive/projects/PXD015488"}], "identifiers": [{"accession": "MS:1001919", "name": "ProteomeXchange accession number", "value": "PXD015488"}], "instruments": [{"accession": "MS:1002732", "name": "Orbitrap Fusion Lumos"}, {"accession": "MS:1001911", "name": "Q Exactive"}], "keywords": [{"accession": "MS:1001925", "name": "submitter keyword", "value": "epigenetics, histone modification, crotonylation, Gcn5-Ada2-Ada3 (ADA) complex, Esa1- Yng2-Epl1 (Piccolo NuA4) complex, gene transcription"}], "modifications": [{"accession": "MOD:01892", "name": "N6-crotonyl-L-lysine"}, {"accession": "MOD:00394", "name": "acetylated residue"}], "publications": [{"terms": [{"accession": "MS:1002858", "name": "Dataset with its publication pending"}]}], "species": [{"terms": [{"accession": "MS:1001469", "name": "taxonomy: scientific name", "value": "Xenopus laevis (African clawed frog)"}, {"accession": "MS:1001467", "name": "taxonomy: NCBI TaxID", "value": "8355"}]}, {"terms": [{"accession": "MS:1001469", "name": "taxonomy: scientific name", "value": "Saccharomyces cerevisiae (Baker's yeast)"}, {"accession": "MS:1001467", "name": "taxonomy: NCBI TaxID", "value": "4932"}]}], "title": "Gcn5 and Esa1 function as histone crotonyltransferases to regulate crotonylation-dependent transcription"}